  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Develops institutional consequentialism as response to demandingness objection. Argues institutions should bear the consequentialist burden of maximizing good, while individuals are required primarily to establish and maintain appropriate institutions. In special occasions where institutions fail, individuals face more stringent demands, but normal circumstances involve moderate institution-supporting obligations rather than constant maximization.

  RELEVANCE: Suggests giving norms should be institutionalized rather than imposed on individuals directly. Both income-based and asset-based norms could be implemented through tax policy, charitable deduction structures, or wealth tax institutions. Institutional approach may support income-based norms if income taxation is more feasible institutionally than asset taxation, or support asset-based norms if wealth taxation better achieves collective goals. Shifts focus from individual demands to institutional design.

