  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Defends "weak anti-rationalism"—the view that moral requirements need not provide overriding reasons for action—as response to demandingness. Argues that even if morality demands significant sacrifice, this doesn't entail that agents have decisive reason to comply. Distinguishes normative authority of moral requirements from their rational force, allowing morality to be demanding without being rationally tyrannical.

  RELEVANCE: Provides alternative framework for assessing demandingness: even if asset-based norms demand more than income-based norms, this may not generate stronger all-things-considered reasons for action. Allows utilitarian defense of stringent norms while acknowledging their demands may sometimes be outweighed by other considerations. However, this meta-ethical move may seem to undermine moral requirements' practical significance for guiding behavior.

  POSITION: Weak anti-rationalism about morality; separates moral requirements from overriding practical reasons.
  },
